<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15018a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15018a">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15018a"> 18(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ostmantown bridge, old bridge (toll) &mdash; 1st of six, holy water vessel>, Old Bridge</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As the professors and students from <mark>Ostmantown</mark> could not conveniently come and go because of the river Liffey, a bridge of four arches, still standing, was built at the cost of the Friars&apos; Preachers, being the <mark>first of the six bridges</mark> of Dublin, called everywhere to this day, the <mark>Old Bridge</mark>. To repay the cost, a lay Dominican, by leave of the City Council, took a <mark>toll</mark>, and I myself, when a boy, have seen the <mark>holy water vessel</mark> (as tradition had it) for sprinkling the passengers. <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD2"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 222.n2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15194a" href="c15all.htm#c15194a">VI.C.15:194(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
